# Knowledge Checklist — Business Case Development for IT Projects
## Everything you need to know, named with a one-line description

*Tick each item: ✅ know it cold · 🔶 roughly · ❌ blank. Organised by topic with exam weight shown. If you can give the one-line description from memory AND apply it to a case, it's a ✅.*

---

## FOUNDATIONS (underpin everything)

- [ ] **Business case** — an evidence-based argument that an IT investment is worth making; used to initiate, monitor, and evaluate a project.
- [ ] **The three uses** — a business case is to *initiate, monitor, and evaluate*.
- [ ] **Four rigor criteria** — a good business case is plausible, well-reasoned, well-evidenced, well-analysed.
- [ ] **why → what → how logic** — drivers/problem → objective/benefits → project/changes.
- [ ] **As-Is vs To-Be** — current state vs target state; the gap is the benefit.
- [ ] **Business case outline (12 sections)** — exec summary → intro → problem → objective → options → benefits → costs → risks → ethics/CSR → governance → conclusion → appendices.
- [ ] **Nelson (2008) failure rate** — ~2 of 3 IT projects are failures (total failure, cost/time overruns, fewer features).
- [ ] **Nelson's four mistake categories** — People (43%), Process (45%), Product (8%), Technology (4%).
- [ ] **Nelson key finding** — failures are mostly people/process, not technology; none of the top 10 was technology.
- [ ] **Nelson top three mistakes** — poor estimation/scheduling, ineffective stakeholder management, insufficient risk management (each ~half of projects).
- [ ] **Public-sector failure share** — half of the most infamous >$100m failures were public-sector.

