## 1. BENEFITS (5% exam)

- [ ] **Benefits management definition** — organising/managing so that potential benefits from IS/IT are actually *realised*.
- [ ] **Core philosophy** — technology alone yields nothing; benefits come only through organisational change.
- [ ] **From → to shift** — from technology delivery to benefits delivery (value not cost; change-management not IT-implementation; stakeholders involved; benefits review).
- [ ] **Five-step process** — Identify & structure → Plan realisation → Execute → Review & evaluate → Exploit further (iterative).
- [ ] **Why iterative** — objectives get modified and new benefits emerge as options are explored; review loops back.
- [ ] **Business drivers** — internal/external pressures creating the need to change (the "why").
- [ ] **Investment objectives** — organisational outcomes that address drivers; must be SMART; act as success criteria.
- [ ] **SMART** — Specific, Measurable, Achievable, Relevant, Time-bounded.
- [ ] **Benefit ownership** — benefits are specific to a stakeholder ("benefiting") and owned by one ("responsible").
- [ ] **Four benefit types** — Observable → Measurable → Quantifiable → Financial (increasing hardness).
- [ ] **Observable** — judged by criteria using expert judgement.
- [ ] **Measurable** — can measure current level but *cannot forecast the improvement*.
- [ ] **Quantifiable** — the *improvement can be forecast*.
- [ ] **Financial** — a financial formula gives a money value.
- [ ] **Measurable vs Quantifiable (the trap)** — measurable can't forecast improvement; quantifiable can.
- [ ] **"All benefits are measurable in some way"** — Ward & Daniel claim; unmeasurable benefits should be discarded.
- [ ] **Business change** — a new *ongoing* way of working (process change).
- [ ] **Enabling change** — a *one-off* prerequisite enabling the business changes / system operation.
- [ ] **Benefits Dependency Network (BDN)** — diagram linking enablers to benefits; columns: IS/IT enablers → enabling changes → business changes → benefits → objectives (drivers behind).
- [ ] **BDN purpose** — forces every claimed benefit to trace back through the changes needed to deliver it.
- [ ] **ROI** — return relative to cost; if return > cost (ratio > 0) potentially worthwhile; needs initial cost, investment, savings.

