## 2. COSTS (5% exam)

- [ ] **Tangible vs intangible costs** — measurable (hardware) vs hard-to-measure but real (loss of goodwill, customer satisfaction).
- [ ] **Ward & Daniel five cost categories** — purchase; internal development (FTEs); infrastructure; cost of business changes (soft costs); ongoing.
- [ ] **Soft costs** — cost of carrying out business changes (e.g. training); easily underestimated because intangible/behavioural.
- [ ] **TCO (Total Cost of Ownership)** — full whole-life cost (hardware, software, implementation, training, support/maintenance, architecture, data), not just purchase price.
- [ ] **Benefits–costs link** — benefits realised through activities → activities need resources → resources are costs (same BDN chain).
- [ ] **Costs & ways of working** — agile/DevOps reframes costing: fix time/resources, vary scope (vs traditional fixed scope, variable cost).
- [ ] **Expert judgement estimation** — uses heuristics; good for novel domains; but biased and misled by irrelevant info.
- [ ] **Parametric/model estimation** — formula from measurable parameters; treats software as predictable; breaks on scope change.
- [ ] **COCOMO** — the parametric model (Boehm); inputs like source lines of code + cost drivers.
- [ ] **Jørgensen (2004)** — found *no clear winner* between expert and model-based estimation.
- [ ] **Lines of code vs Function Point Analysis** — LOC (simple, language-dependent) vs FPA (counts functions: outputs, inquiries, inputs, internal files, external interfaces).
- [ ] **Estimation best practice** — historical data, explicit assumptions, averages, iterative range-based estimates (cone of uncertainty).

