## 3. RISKS (5% exam)

- [ ] **Risk (PMBOK)** — an uncertain event/condition that, if it occurs, has a positive *or* negative effect on project objectives.
- [ ] **Risk can be positive** — an upside risk is an opportunity, not just a threat.
- [ ] **Risk vs uncertainty (Peixoto)** — risk = known probability ("known unknowns", analysable); uncertainty = unknown probability ("unknown unknowns", not analysable).
- [ ] **Mitigation** — reduces the *probability* of the risk.
- [ ] **Contingency** — reduces the *impact* of the risk.
- [ ] **Reduction formula** — Reduction = Mitigation × Contingency (MULTIPLICATION, not addition).
- [ ] **Exposure formula** — Exposure = Risk − Reduction.
- [ ] **Risk = Probability × Impact** — the underlying relationship mitigation/contingency act on.
- [ ] **Risk management two phases** — Assessment (identify → analyse → prioritise) + Control (plan → resolve → monitor).
- [ ] **PMBOK six processes** — plan risk mgmt, identify, qualitative analysis, quantitative analysis, plan responses, control.
- [ ] **Qualitative analysis** — PxI matrix; colour-coded red (avoid)/yellow (mitigate)/green (monitor).
- [ ] **Quantitative analysis** — numeric, e.g. EMV (Expected Monetary Value) via decision trees, for high-priority risks.
- [ ] **Four risk responses** — Avoid, Mitigate, Transfer, Accept (opportunity twins: Explore, Enhance, Share).
- [ ] **"Accept" caveat** — even accepting a risk needs a documented response plan.
- [ ] **Risk register** — the main, continuously-updated output: one record per risk (description, evaluation, response, owner, status).
- [ ] **Risk breakdown structure** — classifies risks by source (external, commercial, project-management, technical).

