## 4. ETHICS (10% exam — heaviest, joint)

- [ ] **Ethics ≠ "the right decision"** — it's the field studying what's good/right; multiple perspectives; no typical right answer.
- [ ] **Ethics vs morality** — morality = norms/values actually held; ethics = systematic reflection on those norms.
- [ ] **Aristotle (virtue ethics)** — right action flows from good character / living up to full potential (the good life).
- [ ] **Kant (categorical imperative / deontology)** — act on universalizable principles; treat people as ends, not merely means; duty over consequences.
- [ ] **Habermas (discourse ethics)** — legitimacy via pure, power-balanced, inclusive dialogue; communicative reason over instrumental; engagement-as-strategy is "amoral".
- [ ] **Levinas** — ethics begins in the face-to-face encounter and responsibility for the vulnerable Other.
- [ ] **Machiavelli** — strategic realism; results and power; ends can justify means; instrumental engagement.
- [ ] **Applying angles (the exam skill)** — run an IT case through ≥2 lenses and show they *conflict*; don't pick a winner.
- [ ] **Two business-ethics camps (Noland & Phillips 2010)** — Habermas discourse ethics vs ethical strategists.
- [ ] **Habermas camp** — engagement moral only as pure, non-instrumental dialogue.
- [ ] **Ethical strategists camp** — ethical engagement *ought* to be part of strategy; business = value for all stakeholders; rejects the separation thesis; Aristotelian/utilitarian.
- [ ] **Separation thesis (rejected)** — the idea that business value and stakeholder/social value can be cleanly separated.
- [ ] **Smart city definition** — contested; Caragliu et al. (2009): social + ICT + life + economy + sustainable + participation.
- [ ] **SIS** — Smart Information Systems (Big Data + AI) underpinning smart cities.
- [ ] **Ryan & Gregory (2019) four categories** — conflicts of interest & bias; economic pressure; inequalities; privacy.
- [ ] **Conflict of interest** — vendors (e.g. IBM) sell SIS to cities while also ranking those cities on their index (self-serving).
- [ ] **Bias** — over-emphasis on technical fixes instead of political/social solutions (Kitchin 2015).
- [ ] **Inequalities** — job replacement by AI, digital divide, rural decline, power/wealth gaps.
- [ ] **Privacy** — data control/ownership, tracking (Enschede WiFi example), recognition, security-vs-privacy.
- [ ] **Measures to address smart-city ethics** — anonymisation/aggregation, informed consent, algorithmic auditing, data agreements, object-over-personal data, bottom-up collaboration.
- [ ] **Risk vs ethical issue (NEAR-CERTAIN)** — risk = uncertain event affecting project outcomes; ethical issue = viewpoint-dependent moral impact on stakeholders/society, about norms and values.
- [ ] **Risk that is NOT an ethical issue** — budget overrun, unforeseen operational costs, temporary non-critical performance dip.
- [ ] **Ethical impact analysis (method)** — identify implications (not necessarily a risk), weigh opposing views, set aside own bias, apply angles, map to UN SDGs reflecting positive AND negative external effects.

