## 5. PUBLIC SECTOR (10% exam — heaviest, joint; EXAM-ONLY)

- [ ] **Public/private taxonomy** — private = for-profit + NPOs; public = government + semi-government agencies (Sethibe et al. 2007).
- [ ] **Winkler (2013) comparison table** — ten attributes contrasting private vs public, with IT-governance implications.
- [ ] **Goals** — private: shareholder value; public: multifaceted public value.
- [ ] **Stakeholders** — private: few; public: many / conflicting.
- [ ] **Environment** — private: less regulated; public: legal/formal constraints.
- [ ] **Incentives** — private: high/market; public: low / "soft budgets" / scrutiny.
- [ ] **Risks** — private: lower aversion; public: high aversion.
- [ ] **Competition** — private: high; public: low / intergovernmental cooperation.
- [ ] **IT innovation** — private: competitive advantage; public: treated as necessity.
- [ ] **IT competencies** — public: generally lower.
- [ ] **IT sourcing** — private: flexible contracting; public: complex tendering/procurement.
- [ ] **IT resources** — private: proprietary; public: shared.
- [ ] **Why it's harder** — can't justify on NPV alone; multifaceted public value, conflicting stakeholders, legal/procurement constraints, scrutiny, risk-aversion.
- [ ] **Public-sector examples (Ryan & Gregory)** — Helsinki protects jobs over efficiency; Copenhagen kept project running for citizen value beyond commercial logic.

