## 8. TOOLS (5% exam — the only CALCULATION skill)

- [ ] **NPV/IRR shortcoming** — static, single-number view; ignores managerial flexibility; undervalues uncertain projects (Mun 2002).
- [ ] **Real options value** — value = static NPV + option premium (premium = value of flexibility).
- [ ] **Real options definition (Amram et al. 1999)** — narrow: extending financial option-pricing to real (non-financial) assets; broad: a way of thinking about strategic options / future opportunities from today's investments.
- [ ] **Long-term strategic, not operational** — real options is for long-term strategic decisions.
- [ ] **Call vs put option** — call = right to buy; put = right to sell.
- [ ] **Long vs short** — long = buy the option; short = sell it; you pay for the right, not the asset.
- [ ] **Option = right not obligation** — real options are the right but not obligation to act (defer/expand/abandon/contract).
- [ ] **Option types (Mun 2012)** — defer/wait, expand, contract, abandon, growth, choose, switch, phased/sequential.
- [ ] **Probability/chance node** — outcomes by random events with known probabilities; value = expected (probability-weighted) value; probabilities sum to 1.
- [ ] **Decision node** — decision-maker chooses; value = maximum of available options.
- [ ] **Backward induction** — start at the end of the horizon, compute each preceding node back to the start.
- [ ] **Option value calculation** — value-with-option − value-without-option (e.g. 100 − 50 = 50).
- [ ] **Decision-tree exam method** — draw tree → probability-weight chance branches → subtract cost → compare branches → recommend.
- [ ] **PRINCE2 business case** — balances Benefits against Cost and Risk.
- [ ] **Continued business justification** — PRINCE2's key principle; the case is checked at each stage; stop if justification is lost.

